To delete a middle node in a linked list in JavaScript, you would typically need to do the following steps:

Traverse the list to find the previous node of the one you want to delete.
Update the next reference of the previous node to point to the node that comes after the one you want to delete (skip the one you want to delete).
Set the next reference of the node you want to delete to null to disconnect it from the list.
Here's an example of a function that deletes a middle node in a singly linked list:

Copy code
function deleteMiddleNode(nodeToDelete) {
    if (!nodeToDelete || !nodeToDelete.next) {
        return false; // the node is the last or not exist
    }
    // Copy the data from the next node over to the current node
    nodeToDelete.data = nodeToDelete.next.data;
    // Update the next reference to skip the next node
    nodeToDelete.next = nodeToDelete.next.next;
    return true;
}
This function takes a single argument, the node that we want to delete and it's work by copying the data from the next node over to the current node, and update the next reference to skip the next node.
Please note that in this example, the function doesn't check if the given node is the head or tail of the list.
